<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-553-702  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 553 702.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  August 21 1989 v23 n34 p39(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IRS laptop gains not realized: move to Zenith portables didn'tboost efficiency, government study finds.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Betts, Mitch.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The IRS has failed to realize the gains it had hoped for when itawarded a contract for 18,000 laptop microcomputers in 1986.andP;  Thegovernment agency had hoped that the computers would vastlyincrease the productivity of its field auditors, therebyincreasing tax revenue, but a study by the General AccountingOffice has found that these benefits have not been realized.andP;  Theprimary reason is serious software development problems whichincreased the complexity of the auditor's task and resulted inmany auditors abandoning the machines completely.andP;  Another problemwas brought about the by IRS's decision to change the programminglanguage used for the custom software from Turbo Pascal to Cprogramming language.andP;  The software still has not been completelyrewritten.andP;  Overall, the IRS's automation project is six yearsbehind schedule and will cost $800 million more than originallyestimated.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Internal Revenue ServiceLaptop computersEfficiencyAuditingCustom SoftwareGovernment ContractsProductivity.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   IRS cost estimations for its Automated Examination System. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>